Note:
Work-stealing thread pool — the public load-balancing executor for the Runa
runtime concurrency system.

A work-stealing pool spreads independent tasks across a fixed set of worker
threads while keeping every core busy. Each worker owns a private double-ended
task queue (a deque). The owner of a deque pushes and pops at its BOTTOM; an
idle worker that has drained its own deque STEALS from the TOP of another
worker's deque. Touching opposite ends keeps the owner and the thief out of
each other's way almost all of the time, so contention stays low even though
the design is fully synchronous and verifiable.

CORRECTNESS-FIRST DESIGN — MUTEX-PROTECTED DEQUES, NOT LOCK-FREE:
This module deliberately protects each deque with its own RuntimeMutex rather
than implementing a lock-free Chase-Lev deque. The owner locks its OWN deque to
push/pop the bottom; a thief locks the VICTIM'S deque to steal from the top.
Because every read and every write of a deque's head/tail/count/ring happens
under that deque's single mutex, every deque operation is a complete critical
section: no two threads ever observe or mutate the same deque's indices
concurrently, which makes the classic owner-vs-thief and thief-vs-thief races
impossible by construction. A subtly racy lock-free deque is worse than a
correct locked one; the per-deque lock is the production-correct choice, and it
stays cheap because a worker overwhelmingly touches only its own deque.

IDLE-WAIT SIGNAL — ONE COUNTING SEMAPHORE:
A single counting semaphore ("tasks available") spans all deques. Every submit
releases one permit; every worker iteration acquires one permit before looking
for work, so idle workers BLOCK on the OS instead of spinning the CPU. Permit
accounting is exact: submit releases exactly one permit per task and shutdown
releases exactly one permit per worker, so every task is executed exactly once
and every worker receives exactly one "no work, shutting down" wake and exits.

DRAIN SIGNAL — PENDING COUNTER + CONDITION VARIABLE:
A mutex-guarded pending counter tracks tasks submitted but not yet completed.
ws_wait_idle blocks on a condition variable until pending reaches zero; the
worker that completes the last task broadcasts that condition. The round-robin
submit cursor lives under the same pending mutex.

WorkStealingPool layout (80 bytes):
    offset 0:  worker_count   — number of worker threads / deques
    offset 8:  deques         — pointer to worker_count deque pointers
    offset 16: tids           — pointer to worker_count thread-id pointers
    offset 24: contexts       — pointer to worker_count worker-context pointers
    offset 32: tasks_sem      — RuntimeSemaphore "tasks available" signal
    offset 40: shutdown       — 0 running, 1 draining-then-exit
    offset 48: pending        — tasks submitted but not yet completed
    offset 56: pending_mutex  — RuntimeMutex guarding pending + rr cursor
    offset 64: drained_cv     — RuntimeCondVar signalled when pending hits 0
    offset 72: rr_cursor      — round-robin index for submit placement

WorkerContext layout (16 bytes):
    offset 0:  pool           — the owning WorkStealingPool
    offset 8:  worker_index   — this worker's index into the deque array

Deque layout (48 bytes):
    offset 0:  mutex          — RuntimeMutex guarding this deque
    offset 8:  ring           — pointer to capacity (fn,arg) task slots
    offset 16: head           — index of the steal (top) end
    offset 24: tail           — index of the push/pop (bottom) end
    offset 32: count          — number of tasks currently held
    offset 40: capacity       — number of task slots in the ring

Task slot layout (16 bytes): fn pointer at +0, arg pointer at +8.
:End Note

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/threading/thread_core.runa" as Thread
Import "runtime/concurrency/synchronization/mutex.runa" as Mutex
Import "runtime/concurrency/synchronization/semaphore.runa" as Sem
Import "runtime/concurrency/synchronization/condition_variable.runa" as CondVar
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/assembly/call_indirect.runa" as Call

Note: Status codes returned by the work-stealing pool API
Constant WS_OK as Integer is 0
Constant WS_ERR_NULL as Integer is 0 minus 1
Constant WS_ERR_ALLOC as Integer is 0 minus 2

Note: WorkStealingPool object layout
Constant WS_POOL_SIZE as Integer is 80
Constant WS_POOL_OFF_WORKER_COUNT as Integer is 0
Constant WS_POOL_OFF_DEQUES as Integer is 8
Constant WS_POOL_OFF_TIDS as Integer is 16
Constant WS_POOL_OFF_CONTEXTS as Integer is 24
Constant WS_POOL_OFF_SEM as Integer is 32
Constant WS_POOL_OFF_SHUTDOWN as Integer is 40
Constant WS_POOL_OFF_PENDING as Integer is 48
Constant WS_POOL_OFF_PENDING_MUTEX as Integer is 56
Constant WS_POOL_OFF_DRAINED_CV as Integer is 64
Constant WS_POOL_OFF_RR as Integer is 72

Note: WorkerContext object layout
Constant WS_CTX_SIZE as Integer is 16
Constant WS_CTX_OFF_POOL as Integer is 0
Constant WS_CTX_OFF_INDEX as Integer is 8

Note: Deque object layout
Constant WS_DQ_SIZE as Integer is 48
Constant WS_DQ_OFF_MUTEX as Integer is 0
Constant WS_DQ_OFF_RING as Integer is 8
Constant WS_DQ_OFF_HEAD as Integer is 16
Constant WS_DQ_OFF_TAIL as Integer is 24
Constant WS_DQ_OFF_COUNT as Integer is 32
Constant WS_DQ_OFF_CAPACITY as Integer is 40

Note: Task slot geometry and the initial per-deque capacity
Constant WS_TASK_SIZE as Integer is 16
Constant WS_TASK_OFF_FN as Integer is 0
Constant WS_TASK_OFF_ARG as Integer is 8
Constant WS_DQ_INIT_CAP as Integer is 64

Note: Pointer-array element stride (one 8-byte pointer per worker)
Constant WS_PTR_SIZE as Integer is 8

Process called "ws_deque_new" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Build one worker's private deque: its guarding mutex and a growable ring of
    (fn,arg) task slots. The deque starts empty with head and tail at zero.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocate the 48-byte deque header, create its RuntimeMutex, allocate the
    initial ring of WS_DQ_INIT_CAP task slots, and initialise head, tail, and
    count to zero with capacity set to the initial size. Any allocation failure
    unwinds every resource acquired so far and returns 0.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Two allocations plus one mutex_new. Cold path: run once per worker at pool
    construction, never on the steal/submit hot path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Returns 0 on any failure; callers MUST check before storing the deque.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let dq be proc allocate from Memory with WS_DQ_SIZE
    If dq is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let mtx be proc mutex_new from Mutex
    If mtx is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with dq
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ring_bytes be WS_DQ_INIT_CAP multiplied by WS_TASK_SIZE
    Let ring be proc allocate from Memory with ring_bytes
    If ring is equal to 0:
        proc mutex_destroy from Mutex with mtx
        proc deallocate from Memory with dq
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_MUTEX, mtx
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_RING, ring
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_HEAD, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_TAIL, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_COUNT, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_CAPACITY, WS_DQ_INIT_CAP
    Return dq
End Process

Process called "ws_deque_destroy" takes dq as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release every resource a deque owns: its ring buffer, its mutex, and the
    deque header itself. Called only during pool teardown, after all workers
    have stopped, so no thread can be inside the deque's critical section.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Free the ring, destroy the mutex, then deallocate the header. Each field is
    null-checked so a partially constructed deque can be torn down safely.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One deallocate, one mutex_destroy, one deallocate. Cold path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null deque is a no-op returning WS_OK. Destroying a deque while a worker
    could still touch it is a caller logic error prevented by joining first.
    @End Security_Scope

    If dq is equal to 0:
        Return WS_OK
    End If

    Let ring be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_RING
    If ring is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with ring
    End If

    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_MUTEX
    If mtx is not equal to 0:
        proc mutex_destroy from Mutex with mtx
    End If

    proc deallocate from Memory with dq
    Return WS_OK
End Process

Process called "ws_deque_grow" takes dq as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Double a full deque's ring so a push never has to drop a task. The live
    tasks form a logical sequence from head forward (wrapping at capacity); the
    grow copies that sequence into a fresh contiguous buffer and re-bases the
    indices so head is 0 and tail is count.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Allocate a buffer of twice the current capacity. Walk the count live tasks
    in logical order starting at head (modulo old capacity), copying each
    (fn,arg) pair into slot i of the new buffer. Publish the new ring, reset
    head to 0 and tail to count, store the new capacity, and free the old ring.
    Caller holds the deque mutex, so the resize is atomic with respect to every
    other deque operation. Returns WS_ERR_ALLOC if the new buffer cannot be
    allocated, leaving the original ring intact.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One allocation plus a count-element copy. Amortised O(1) per push because
    capacity doubles, so the copy cost is spread across the inserts since the
    last grow. Rare on steady-state workloads sized near the initial capacity.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Must be called while holding the deque mutex. On allocation failure the
    deque is unchanged and remains fully usable.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let old_cap be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_CAPACITY
    Let new_cap be old_cap multiplied by 2
    Let old_ring be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_RING
    Let cnt be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_COUNT
    Let head be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_HEAD

    Let new_bytes be new_cap multiplied by WS_TASK_SIZE
    Let new_ring be proc allocate from Memory with new_bytes
    If new_ring is equal to 0:
        Return WS_ERR_ALLOC
    End If

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than cnt:
        Let logical be head plus i
        Let src_idx be logical modulo by old_cap
        Let src_off be src_idx multiplied by WS_TASK_SIZE
        Let src_fn_off be src_off plus WS_TASK_OFF_FN
        Let src_arg_off be src_off plus WS_TASK_OFF_ARG
        Let fn be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with old_ring, src_fn_off
        Let arg be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with old_ring, src_arg_off

        Let dst_off be i multiplied by WS_TASK_SIZE
        Let dst_fn_off be dst_off plus WS_TASK_OFF_FN
        Let dst_arg_off be dst_off plus WS_TASK_OFF_ARG
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with new_ring, dst_fn_off, fn
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with new_ring, dst_arg_off, arg

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_RING, new_ring
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_HEAD, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_TAIL, cnt
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_CAPACITY, new_cap
    proc deallocate from Memory with old_ring
    Return WS_OK
End Process

Process called "ws_deque_push_bottom" takes dq as Integer, fn as Integer, arg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Append a task at the deque's bottom — the end the owning worker (and a
    submitter routing work here) uses. Growing first guarantees the push always
    succeeds when memory is available.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Lock the deque. If it is full, grow it (and refresh the capacity). Store the
    (fn,arg) pair at the tail slot, advance tail modulo capacity, bump count,
    and unlock. Returns WS_ERR_ALLOC (without inserting) if a needed grow fails.
    The internal deque mutex is never poisoned by this module, so the acquire
    always returns with the lock held.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mutex round-trip plus two stores on the common path; an extra resize
    only when the ring is full.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    The lock is always released before returning on every path, including the
    grow-failure path.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with mtx

    Let cnt be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_COUNT
    Let cap be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_CAPACITY
    If cnt is greater than or equal to cap:
        Let g be proc ws_deque_grow with dq
        If g is not equal to WS_OK:
            proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
            Return g
        End If
        Set cap to proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_CAPACITY
    End If

    Let ring be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_RING
    Let tail be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_TAIL
    Let off be tail multiplied by WS_TASK_SIZE
    Let fn_off be off plus WS_TASK_OFF_FN
    Let arg_off be off plus WS_TASK_OFF_ARG
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with ring, fn_off, fn
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with ring, arg_off, arg

    Let next_tail_raw be tail plus 1
    Let next_tail be next_tail_raw modulo by cap
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_TAIL, next_tail
    Let new_count be cnt plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_COUNT, new_count

    proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
    Return WS_OK
End Process

Process called "ws_deque_pop_bottom" takes dq as Integer, out_buf as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    The owning worker takes its most recently pushed task from the bottom. LIFO
    on the owner's own end gives good cache locality and leaves the older tasks
    at the top for thieves, so owners and thieves rarely touch the same slot.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Lock the deque. If empty, unlock and report 0. Otherwise step tail back one
    slot modulo capacity, read the (fn,arg) pair there into out_buf, decrement
    count, unlock, and report 1.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mutex round-trip plus two loads. The owner's hot path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    out_buf must point to at least 16 writable bytes. The lock is released on
    both the empty and the success path. Returns 1 when a task was written,
    0 when the deque was empty.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with mtx

    Let cnt be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_COUNT
    If cnt is equal to 0:
        proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
        Return 0
    End If

    Let cap be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_CAPACITY
    Let tail be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_TAIL
    Let tail_back be tail plus cap
    Set tail_back to tail_back minus 1
    Let new_tail be tail_back modulo by cap

    Let ring be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_RING
    Let off be new_tail multiplied by WS_TASK_SIZE
    Let fn_off be off plus WS_TASK_OFF_FN
    Let arg_off be off plus WS_TASK_OFF_ARG
    Let fn be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with ring, fn_off
    Let arg be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with ring, arg_off

    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_TAIL, new_tail
    Let new_count be cnt minus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_COUNT, new_count

    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with out_buf, WS_TASK_OFF_FN, fn
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with out_buf, WS_TASK_OFF_ARG, arg

    proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "ws_deque_steal_top" takes dq as Integer, out_buf as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    A thief takes the OLDEST task from a victim deque's top. Stealing the
    opposite end from where the owner works minimises contention and tends to
    move a larger sub-tree of work to the idle thief in divide-and-conquer
    workloads.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Lock the victim deque. If empty, unlock and report 0. Otherwise read the
    (fn,arg) pair at head into out_buf, advance head one slot modulo capacity,
    decrement count, unlock, and report 1.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One mutex round-trip plus two loads. Runs only when a worker has drained its
    own deque, so it is off the common path.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    out_buf must point to at least 16 writable bytes. The lock is released on
    both the empty and the success path. Returns 1 when a task was written,
    0 when the victim was empty.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let mtx be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_MUTEX
    proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with mtx

    Let cnt be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_COUNT
    If cnt is equal to 0:
        proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
        Return 0
    End If

    Let cap be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_CAPACITY
    Let head be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_HEAD
    Let ring be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_RING
    Let off be head multiplied by WS_TASK_SIZE
    Let fn_off be off plus WS_TASK_OFF_FN
    Let arg_off be off plus WS_TASK_OFF_ARG
    Let fn be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with ring, fn_off
    Let arg be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with ring, arg_off

    Let next_head_raw be head plus 1
    Let next_head be next_head_raw modulo by cap
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_HEAD, next_head
    Let new_count be cnt minus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with dq, WS_DQ_OFF_COUNT, new_count

    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with out_buf, WS_TASK_OFF_FN, fn
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with out_buf, WS_TASK_OFF_ARG, arg

    proc mutex_release from Mutex with mtx
    Return 1
End Process

Process called "ws_try_get_task" takes pool as Integer, my_index as Integer, out_buf as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Find one task for a worker: prefer the worker's own deque (LIFO, cache-warm),
    and only when it is empty steal from someone else. The steal scan visits
    EVERY other worker before giving up so no runnable task is ever overlooked.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Pop the bottom of the worker's own deque first; on success report 1. On an
    empty own deque, walk the other workers round-robin starting at the next
    index (my_index + 1 .. my_index + worker_count - 1, each modulo
    worker_count) and try to steal each victim's top. Report 1 as soon as a
    steal succeeds, or 0 after every other deque has been checked and found
    empty.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One own-deque pop on the common path. The steal scan costs up to
    worker_count - 1 lock attempts and runs only when a worker is otherwise
    idle, so it never burdens the busy case.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    out_buf must point to at least 16 writable bytes. Pure work-finding: touches
    only deque state through their own locks.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let n be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_WORKER_COUNT
    Let deques be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_DEQUES

    Let own_off be my_index multiplied by WS_PTR_SIZE
    Let own_dq be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with deques, own_off
    Let got be proc ws_deque_pop_bottom with own_dq, out_buf
    If got is equal to 1:
        Return 1
    End If

    Let i be 1
    While i is less than n:
        Let raw be my_index plus i
        Let victim_idx be raw modulo by n
        Let victim_off be victim_idx multiplied by WS_PTR_SIZE
        Let victim_dq be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with deques, victim_off
        Let stolen be proc ws_deque_steal_top with victim_dq, out_buf
        If stolen is equal to 1:
            Return 1
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "ws_complete_one" takes pool as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Record that one task finished. When the count of outstanding tasks reaches
    zero, any thread blocked in ws_wait_idle must be woken, so completion of the
    last task broadcasts the drained condition.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Under the pending mutex, decrement the pending counter; if it reached zero,
    broadcast the drained condition variable while still holding the mutex so
    the wake is published before any waiter re-checks the predicate. Release the
    mutex and return.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One short critical section per completed task: a decrement and an occasional
    broadcast only on the final task.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Must balance exactly one ws_complete_one against each counted submit so the
    pending counter cannot underflow.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let pm be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_PENDING_MUTEX
    proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with pm

    Let pending be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_PENDING
    Let new_pending be pending minus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_PENDING, new_pending
    If new_pending is equal to 0:
        Let cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_DRAINED_CV
        proc condvar_broadcast from CondVar with cv
    End If

    proc mutex_release from Mutex with pm
    Return WS_OK
End Process

Process called "ws_worker_main" takes ctx as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    The body each worker thread runs. A worker blocks on the shared semaphore
    until a task exists (or shutdown wakes it), claims one task from its own
    deque or by stealing, runs it, and accounts for its completion — looping
    until shutdown leaves no work anywhere.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Read the pool and this worker's index from the context, cache the semaphore,
    and allocate one 16-byte scratch buffer reused for every claimed task. Then
    loop forever: acquire one permit (blocking while idle), try to get a task
    (own pop then exhaustive steal scan). If a task is obtained, invoke it via
    call_indirect_1(fn, arg) and call ws_complete_one. If no task is found and
    shutdown is set, free the scratch buffer and exit; if no task is found while
    still running, yield and loop to re-block. Permit accounting guarantees every
    counted task is run exactly once and every worker receives exactly one
    shutdown wake on which it exits.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    The hot path is one semaphore acquire, one own-deque pop, one indirect call,
    and one counter decrement. Idle workers sleep in the OS on the semaphore
    rather than spinning; the defensive yield only runs on the rare race where a
    permit's task was already claimed by a peer.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    A null context returns immediately. The scratch buffer is freed on the
    shutdown exit path so a cleanly shut-down pool leaks nothing.
    @End Security_Scope

    If ctx is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let pool be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with ctx, WS_CTX_OFF_POOL
    Let my_index be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with ctx, WS_CTX_OFF_INDEX
    Let sem be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_SEM

    Let task_buf be proc allocate from Memory with WS_TASK_SIZE
    If task_buf is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Loop forever:
        proc semaphore_acquire from Sem with sem

        Let got be proc ws_try_get_task with pool, my_index, task_buf
        If got is equal to 1:
            Let fn be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with task_buf, WS_TASK_OFF_FN
            Let arg be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with task_buf, WS_TASK_OFF_ARG
            proc call_indirect_1 from Call with fn, arg
            proc ws_complete_one with pool
        Otherwise:
            Let sd be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_SHUTDOWN
            If sd is not equal to 0:
                proc deallocate from Memory with task_buf
                Return 0
            End If
            proc thread_yield from Thread
        End If
    End Loop

    Return 0
End Process

Process called "ws_free_pool_memory" takes pool as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Release every resource a fully-initialised pool owns once no worker is
    running: each deque, each worker context, the three pointer arrays, the
    semaphore, the pending mutex, the drained condition variable, and the pool
    header. Used both by the failure-cleanup paths in ws_new and by ws_shutdown
    after all workers have been joined.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Iterate the deque array destroying each non-null deque, then free that array.
    Iterate the context array deallocating each non-null context, then free that
    array. Free the tids array (the thread structures themselves are freed by
    thread_join). Destroy the semaphore, pending mutex, and drained condvar if
    present. Finally deallocate the pool header. Every field is null-checked so
    a pool whose worker/deque arrays were only partially populated (with the
    unused slots pre-zeroed) tears down safely.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Linear in worker_count. Cold path: runs once per pool at shutdown or on a
    construction failure.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Requires that no worker thread is still running against this pool. ws_new
    only calls it after joining any spawned workers; ws_shutdown joins first.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let n be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_WORKER_COUNT

    Let deques be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_DEQUES
    If deques is not equal to 0:
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than n:
            Let off be i multiplied by WS_PTR_SIZE
            Let dq be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with deques, off
            If dq is not equal to 0:
                proc ws_deque_destroy with dq
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        proc deallocate from Memory with deques
    End If

    Let contexts be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_CONTEXTS
    If contexts is not equal to 0:
        Let j be 0
        While j is less than n:
            Let coff be j multiplied by WS_PTR_SIZE
            Let c be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with contexts, coff
            If c is not equal to 0:
                proc deallocate from Memory with c
            End If
            Set j to j plus 1
        End While
        proc deallocate from Memory with contexts
    End If

    Let tids be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_TIDS
    If tids is not equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with tids
    End If

    Let sem be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_SEM
    If sem is not equal to 0:
        proc semaphore_destroy from Sem with sem
    End If

    Let pm be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_PENDING_MUTEX
    If pm is not equal to 0:
        proc mutex_destroy from Mutex with pm
    End If

    Let cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_DRAINED_CV
    If cv is not equal to 0:
        proc condvar_destroy from CondVar with cv
    End If

    proc deallocate from Memory with pool
    Return WS_OK
End Process

Process called "ws_new" takes worker_count as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Construct a ready-to-run work-stealing pool: per-worker deques, the shared
    task semaphore, the pending mutex and drained condition variable, one
    context per worker, and one running worker thread per deque. A non-positive
    worker_count defers to the hardware thread count so the pool fills the
    machine by default.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Normalise worker_count (<=0 becomes thread_hardware_concurrency, floored at
    1). Allocate the pool header, the deque/tids/context pointer arrays, the
    semaphore seeded at 0, the pending mutex, and the drained condvar, unwinding
    cleanly on any early failure. Initialise every pool field and pre-zero the
    three arrays so partial cleanup is safe. Create each deque; on failure tear
    down via ws_free_pool_memory. Then, for each worker, allocate its context,
    store it, take ws_worker_main's address with the $ function-pointer operator,
    and spawn the thread; on a spawn failure set shutdown, release one permit per
    already-spawned worker, join them, and free everything. Return the pool, or 0
    on any failure.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Cold path run once. Allocations are O(worker_count); thread creation
    dominates. Workers immediately block on the empty semaphore until work is
    submitted, so construction adds no busy-wait.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Returns 0 on every failure with all partial resources released and any
    already-spawned workers joined, so a failed construction leaks nothing and
    leaves no threads running.
    @End Security_Scope

    Let n be worker_count
    If n is less than or equal to 0:
        Set n to proc thread_hardware_concurrency from Thread
        If n is less than 1:
            Set n to 1
        End If
    End If

    Let pool be proc allocate from Memory with WS_POOL_SIZE
    If pool is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let arr_bytes be n multiplied by WS_PTR_SIZE

    Let deques be proc allocate from Memory with arr_bytes
    If deques is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with pool
        Return 0
    End If

    Let tids be proc allocate from Memory with arr_bytes
    If tids is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with deques
        proc deallocate from Memory with pool
        Return 0
    End If

    Let contexts be proc allocate from Memory with arr_bytes
    If contexts is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with tids
        proc deallocate from Memory with deques
        proc deallocate from Memory with pool
        Return 0
    End If

    Let sem be proc semaphore_new from Sem with 0
    If sem is equal to 0:
        proc deallocate from Memory with contexts
        proc deallocate from Memory with tids
        proc deallocate from Memory with deques
        proc deallocate from Memory with pool
        Return 0
    End If

    Let pm be proc mutex_new from Mutex
    If pm is equal to 0:
        proc semaphore_destroy from Sem with sem
        proc deallocate from Memory with contexts
        proc deallocate from Memory with tids
        proc deallocate from Memory with deques
        proc deallocate from Memory with pool
        Return 0
    End If

    Let cv be proc condvar_new from CondVar
    If cv is equal to 0:
        proc mutex_destroy from Mutex with pm
        proc semaphore_destroy from Sem with sem
        proc deallocate from Memory with contexts
        proc deallocate from Memory with tids
        proc deallocate from Memory with deques
        proc deallocate from Memory with pool
        Return 0
    End If

    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_WORKER_COUNT, n
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_DEQUES, deques
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_TIDS, tids
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_CONTEXTS, contexts
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_SEM, sem
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_SHUTDOWN, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_PENDING, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_PENDING_MUTEX, pm
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_DRAINED_CV, cv
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_RR, 0

    Let z be 0
    While z is less than n:
        Let zoff be z multiplied by WS_PTR_SIZE
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with deques, zoff, 0
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tids, zoff, 0
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with contexts, zoff, 0
        Set z to z plus 1
    End While

    Let d be 0
    While d is less than n:
        Let dq be proc ws_deque_new
        If dq is equal to 0:
            proc ws_free_pool_memory with pool
            Return 0
        End If
        Let doff be d multiplied by WS_PTR_SIZE
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with deques, doff, dq
        Set d to d plus 1
    End While

    Let w be 0
    While w is less than n:
        Let ctx be proc allocate from Memory with WS_CTX_SIZE
        If ctx is equal to 0:
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_SHUTDOWN, 1
            Let r1 be 0
            While r1 is less than w:
                proc semaphore_release from Sem with sem
                Set r1 to r1 plus 1
            End While
            Let j1 be 0
            While j1 is less than w:
                Let joff be j1 multiplied by WS_PTR_SIZE
                Let t be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with tids, joff
                If t is not equal to 0:
                    proc thread_join from Thread with t
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tids, joff, 0
                End If
                Set j1 to j1 plus 1
            End While
            proc ws_free_pool_memory with pool
            Return 0
        End If

        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with ctx, WS_CTX_OFF_POOL, pool
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with ctx, WS_CTX_OFF_INDEX, w
        Let woff be w multiplied by WS_PTR_SIZE
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with contexts, woff, ctx

        Let entry be $ws_worker_main
        Let tid be proc thread_create from Thread with entry, ctx
        If tid is equal to 0:
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_SHUTDOWN, 1
            Let r2 be 0
            While r2 is less than w:
                proc semaphore_release from Sem with sem
                Set r2 to r2 plus 1
            End While
            Let j2 be 0
            While j2 is less than w:
                Let joff2 be j2 multiplied by WS_PTR_SIZE
                Let t2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with tids, joff2
                If t2 is not equal to 0:
                    proc thread_join from Thread with t2
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tids, joff2, 0
                End If
                Set j2 to j2 plus 1
            End While
            proc ws_free_pool_memory with pool
            Return 0
        End If

        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tids, woff, tid
        Set w to w plus 1
    End While

    Return pool
End Process

Process called "ws_submit" takes pool as Integer, fn as Integer, arg as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Hand a task to the pool. Tasks are spread across deques round-robin so the
    initial load is balanced; work stealing then re-balances dynamically as
    workers finish at different rates. The pending count rises and a permit is
    released so a sleeping worker wakes to run the task.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Under the pending mutex, read and advance the round-robin cursor (modulo
    worker_count) and increment pending. Push the (fn,arg) task onto the chosen
    deque's bottom, growing its ring if needed. If the push fails to allocate,
    roll the pending counter back (broadcasting drained if it returns to zero so
    a waiter is not stranded) and return the error without releasing a permit.
    On success, release one semaphore permit and return WS_OK.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One short pending-mutex critical section, one deque push (lock plus two
    stores on the common path), and one semaphore signal. No busy-waiting.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null pool returns WS_ERR_NULL. The pending counter is kept exactly balanced
    against completions even on the allocation-failure path.
    @End Security_Scope

    If pool is equal to 0:
        Return WS_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let n be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_WORKER_COUNT
    Let pm be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_PENDING_MUTEX
    Let sem be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_SEM
    Let deques be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_DEQUES

    proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with pm
    Let rr be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_RR
    Let idx be rr modulo by n
    Let next_rr_raw be rr plus 1
    Let next_rr be next_rr_raw modulo by n
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_RR, next_rr
    Let pending be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_PENDING
    Let new_pending be pending plus 1
    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_PENDING, new_pending
    proc mutex_release from Mutex with pm

    Let off be idx multiplied by WS_PTR_SIZE
    Let dq be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with deques, off
    Let pr be proc ws_deque_push_bottom with dq, fn, arg
    If pr is not equal to WS_OK:
        proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with pm
        Let p2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_PENDING
        Let p3 be p2 minus 1
        proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_PENDING, p3
        If p3 is equal to 0:
            Let cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_DRAINED_CV
            proc condvar_broadcast from CondVar with cv
        End If
        proc mutex_release from Mutex with pm
        Return pr
    End If

    proc semaphore_release from Sem with sem
    Return WS_OK
End Process

Process called "ws_pending" takes pool as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Report how many submitted tasks have not yet completed, read under the
    pending mutex so the value is a consistent snapshot rather than a torn read.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Acquire the pending mutex, read the pending counter, release, and return it.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One short critical section: a single load under the lock.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null pool returns WS_ERR_NULL. The count is always non-negative, so the -1
    error sentinel is unambiguous.
    @End Security_Scope

    If pool is equal to 0:
        Return WS_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let pm be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_PENDING_MUTEX
    proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with pm
    Let pending be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_PENDING
    proc mutex_release from Mutex with pm
    Return pending
End Process

Process called "ws_wait_idle" takes pool as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Block the caller until the pool has no outstanding tasks. Used to join a
    batch of submitted work before reading results or shutting down. The wait is
    event-driven on the drained condition variable, never a poll.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Acquire the pending mutex and loop: while pending is non-zero, condvar_wait
    on the drained condition with the pending mutex (which atomically releases
    the mutex, sleeps until ws_complete_one broadcasts, and re-acquires it),
    then re-read pending. The While-predicate re-check makes the wait robust to
    spurious wakeups. Release the mutex once pending is zero and return WS_OK.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Sleeps in the OS until the last task completes; no busy-waiting. Wakes once
    per drain event and re-checks the predicate.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null pool returns WS_ERR_NULL. The pending mutex is held only across the
    predicate checks and is always released before returning.
    @End Security_Scope

    If pool is equal to 0:
        Return WS_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let pm be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_PENDING_MUTEX
    Let cv be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_DRAINED_CV

    proc mutex_acquire from Mutex with pm
    Let pending be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_PENDING
    While pending is not equal to 0:
        proc condvar_wait from CondVar with cv, pm
        Set pending to proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_PENDING
    End While
    proc mutex_release from Mutex with pm
    Return WS_OK
End Process

Process called "ws_worker_count" takes pool as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Report how many worker threads the pool runs, the fixed degree of
    parallelism chosen at construction.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Read and return the worker_count field.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    One field load.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null pool returns WS_ERR_NULL; a live pool always has at least one worker.
    @End Security_Scope

    If pool is equal to 0:
        Return WS_ERR_NULL
    End If
    Return proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_WORKER_COUNT
End Process

Process called "ws_shutdown" takes pool as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
    Stop the pool cleanly: tell workers to finish, wake every one of them, wait
    for them all to exit, then release every resource. Tasks already queued are
    drained before the workers exit because a worker only exits when an
    exhaustive scan finds no task anywhere.
    @End Reasoning

    @Implementation
    Set the shutdown flag, then release exactly one semaphore permit per worker
    so each blocked worker wakes at least once. Join every spawned worker thread
    (thread_join frees each thread structure) and clear its slot. Finally call
    ws_free_pool_memory to destroy the deques, contexts, arrays, semaphore,
    pending mutex, drained condvar, and pool header.
    @End Implementation

    @Performance_Hints
    Cold path run once. Cost is worker_count permit signals plus worker_count
    joins plus linear resource teardown.
    @End Performance_Hints

    @Security_Scope
    Null pool returns WS_ERR_NULL. After this returns the pool pointer is
    invalid and must not be used. Submitting concurrently with shutdown is a
    caller logic error.
    @End Security_Scope

    If pool is equal to 0:
        Return WS_ERR_NULL
    End If

    Let n be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_WORKER_COUNT
    Let sem be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_SEM
    Let tids be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_TIDS

    proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with pool, WS_POOL_OFF_SHUTDOWN, 1

    Let r be 0
    While r is less than n:
        proc semaphore_release from Sem with sem
        Set r to r plus 1
    End While

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than n:
        Let off be i multiplied by WS_PTR_SIZE
        Let tid be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with tids, off
        If tid is not equal to 0:
            proc thread_join from Thread with tid
            proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with tids, off, 0
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    proc ws_free_pool_memory with pool
    Return WS_OK
End Process
